	<exploration xml:id="psa_elec-alpha1">
		<title>Net Charge I</title>
		<statement>
		    <p>In a laboratory, a system is constructed that contains 7 protons and 4 electrons.Â  What is the net charge of this system?</p>
		</statement>
		<answer>
		    <p><m>4.8 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{~C}</m></p>
		</answer>
	</exploration>
	
	<exploration xml:id="psa_elec-alpha2">
		<title>Net Charge II</title>
		<statement>
		    <p>A system of protons and electrons has a net charge of <m>-1.12 \times 10^{-18}  \mathrm{~C}</m>.  If the system contains 15 protons, how many electrons are in the system? </p>
		</statement>
		<answer>
		    <p><m>22</m> electrons</p>
		</answer>
	</exploration>
	
	<exploration xml:id="psa_elec-alpha3">
		<title>Net Charge III</title>
		<statement>
		    <p>An amoeba has <m>1 \times 10^{16}</m> protons and a net charge of <m>0.300 \mathrm{~pC}</m>.  How many fewer electrons are there than protons? </p>
		</statement>
		<answer>
		    <p><m>1.88 \times 10^6</m> fewer electrons</p>
		</answer>
	</exploration>
	
	<exploration xml:id="psa_elec-alpha4">
		<title>Dryer Charge</title>
		<statement>
		    <p>Consider a cotton sock inside a dryer machine whose drum (inner container) is made of steel.  After tumbling around in the dryer's drum for a while, the cotton sock has a net charge on it now.  Which of the following charge transfers most likely happened in this sock-drum system? </p>
				<ol marker="A">
				<li>The steel drum lost electrons while the cotton sock gained those electrons. </li>
				<li>The steel drum lost protons while the cotton sock gained those protons. </li>
				<li>The cotton sock lost electrons while the steel drum gained those electrons. </li>
				<li>The cotton sock lost protons while the steel drum gained those protons. </li>
				<li>Both the cotton sock and steel drum lost electrons.</li>
				<li>Both the cotton sock and the steel drum gained electrons.</li>
				</ol>
		</statement>
		<answer>
		    <p>C</p>
		</answer>
	</exploration>

	<exploration>
		<title>Electric Field of a Point Charge</title>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Consider a positive charge <m>q_1</m> = 4 .00 nC that exists in a space far away from other charges.  What is the electric field at a point P in space that is 15.0 m to the left of this point charge? 
			</p>
		</statement>
		<answer>
			<p>
				<m>\vec{E} = (-0.16 \mathrm{N}/\mathrm{C}) \hat{x}</m>
			</p>
		</answer>
	</exploration>

	<exploration>
		<title>Electric Field of Many Charges</title>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Consider a negative charge <m>q_1</m> = -9.00 nC that exists in a space far away from other charges. Let the charge <m>q_1</m> lie at the origin of a standard coordinate system. What is the electric field at a point P in space that has coordinates  (2, -3, 6) m?
			</p>
		</statement>
		<answer>
			<p>
				<m>\vec{E} = (-0.472 \ \mathrm{N}/\mathrm{C})\hat{x} + (0.708 \ \mathrm{N}/\mathrm{C})\hat{y} + (-1.42 \ \mathrm{N}/\mathrm{C})\hat{z}</m>
			</p>
		</answer>
	</exploration>

